etymologies: mid 17th century; earliest use found in Thomas Herbert. From un- + pitched

definitions: Not smeared, covered, or treated with pitch; (of a road) untarred, unpaved.

etymologies: mid 17th century; earliest use found in James Howell (?1594–1666), historian and political writer. From un- + pitched

definitions: Of a military encounter: not fought at a predetermined time and place; unplanned, unorganized.
Not fixed to the ground with pegs or stakes; (of a tent) not erected or put up.
Of sound: without an assigned pitch.
